06546nam a22010455i 9783110637526DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021944638  a97831106375267 a10.1515/97831106375262doi  a(DE-B1597)507621  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aIlluminating Metalwork :bMetal, Object, and Image in Medieval Manuscripts /ced. by Joseph Salvatore Ackley, Shannon L. Wearing. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIII, 510 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSense, Matter, and Medium : New Approaches to Medieval Literary and Material Culture ,x2367-0290 ;v40 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe presence of gold, silver, and other metals is a hallmark of decorated manuscripts, the very characteristic that makes them “illuminated.” Medieval artists often used metal pigment and leaf to depict metal objects both real and imagined, such as chalices, crosses, tableware, and even idols; the luminosity of these representations contrasted pointedly with the surrounding paints, enriching the page and dazzling the viewer. To elucidate this key artistic tradition, this volume represents the first in-depth scholarly assessment of the depiction of precious-metal objects in manuscripts and the media used to conjure them. From Paris to the Abbasid caliphate, and from Ethiopia to Bruges, the case studies gathered here forge novel approaches to the materiality and pictoriality of illumination. In exploring the semiotic, material, iconographic, and technical dimensions of these manuscripts, the authors reveal the canny ways in which painters generated metallic presence on the page. Illuminating Metalwork is a landmark contribution to the study of the medieval book and its visual and embodied reception, and is poised to be a staple of research in art history and manuscript studies, accessible to undergraduates and specialists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 4aHandschrift. 4aMittelalterliche Kunst. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMedieval art history.  amanuscript studies.  amanuscripts conservation.  ametalwork.1 aAckley, Joseph Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAckley, Joseph Salvatore, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarahal, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetancourt, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuettner, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster-Campbell, Megan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrison, Eliza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGearhart, Heidi C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGnisci, Jacopo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorjeltchan, Sasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Lynley Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeal, Beatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOswald, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPugliano, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRochmes, Sophia Ronan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Nancy K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWearing, Shannon L., econtributor.4ctb4https://i